  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 쪼갠 박 …… 적합 : '
    value: “혜자(惠子)가 장자(莊子)에게 말하기를, ‘내가 큰 박[匏]의 종자를 얻어 심었더니 닷 섬이 들 만한 큰 바가지가 열렸는데 너무 커서 쓸모가 없었다.’ 하니 장자는 말하기를, ‘그러면 큰 디룽박을 만두 강호(江湖)에 띄워 사람이 타고 건너는 것으로 만들면 되지 않는가.’ 하였다.” 《장자(莊子)》
  - key: '[주-D002] 마주(馬周)는 …… 짧았으니 : '
    value: 중서령(中書令)까지 올라갔으나 48세로 죽었다. 처음에 원천강(遠天綱)이 관상을 보고 “빨리 귀히 되나 오래 못갈 것이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 풍당(馮唐)은 …… 탄식 : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 풍당 고제(高帝) 때에 낭관(郎官)이 되어 혜제(惠帝)를 거쳐 문제(文帝) 때에 가서야 문제에게 알아줌을 받았다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 장자방(張子房)은 …… 족하였고 : '
    value: 장량이 말하기를, “내가 포의로 일어나서 만호후를 봉하였으니 나에게 족하다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 이광(李廣)은 …… 하였고 : '
    value: 한나라 이광이 팔이 원숭이 팔처럼 생겨서 활을 잘 쏘았다. 그러나 운수가 박하여 번번히 싸움에는 공을 이루지 못하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 충효(忠孝)가 …… 모여서 : '
    value: 진(晋)나라 변곤(卞壼)이 소준(蘇峻)의 난에 싸우다가 죽으매, 두 아들이 아버지의 죽는 것을 보고 달려가서 함께 죽었다. 그 어머니가 두 아들의 시체를 어루만지며 울기를, “아버지는 충신이 되고 아들은 효자가 되었으니, 충효가 일문(一門)에 모였구나.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 단지(丹墀)에 …… 되니 : '
    value: 낭관(郞官)을 성관(星官)이라 하는데, 하늘에 낭관성(郞官星)이 있는 때문이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 우씨(于氏)의 음공(陰功) : '
    value: 한나라 우공(于公)이 옥관(獄官)이 되어 원통한 죄수를 많이 살렸으므로 스스로 말하기를 “내가 음공(陰功)이 있으니 반드시 자손이 잘 되리라 하더니 그의 아들 정국(定國)이 정승이 되었다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 아침 저녁 …… 것이요 : '
    value: 《장자》에, “성인이 5백년 만에 하나씩 나면 그것은 아침 저녁에 만나는 것과 같은 것이다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 외루(畏壘)의 …… 않았고 : '
    value: 《장자》에 노자(老子)의 제자인 경상초(庚桑楚)가 외루(畏壘)에 있으니, 3년 동안 큰 풍년이 들었다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 장창(張敞)의 뜻 : '
    value: 한나라 장창이 임지(任地)로 가는 곳마다 도적이 자취를 감추었다 한다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 위궐(魏闕)을 …… 걸고 : '
    value: 《장자(莊子)》에 공자모(公子牟)가, “몸은 강해(江海) 위에 있으나, 마음은 위궐(魏闕) 아래 있도다.” 하였다. 위궐은 궁성(宮城)의 정문(正門)으로 법령을 계시하던 곳.
  - key: '[주-D013] 선실(宣室) : '
    value: 한(漢)나라 미앙궁(未央宮) 전전(前殿) 정실(正室)인데, 여기서 효문제(孝文帝)가 가의(賈誼)를 불러서 귀신(鬼神)의 근본에 대해서 물었다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 조정에 …… 없고 : '
    value: 한나라 선제(先帝) 때 귀성(貴盛)하던 김일제(金日磾)와 장안세(張安世)의 집안을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 나에게 …… 없으므로 : '
    value: 한나라 때에, “소(蕭)ㆍ주(朱)가 인끈을 차매 왕(王)ㆍ공(貢)이 갓을 털고 좋아한다.”는 말이 있다. 그것은 네 사람이 서로 친하여 잘 되기를 바란다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 동관(潼關)의 …… 들어가고 : '
    value: 당나라 한유(韓愈)가 동관(潼關)의 백욕(白鵒) 새를 임금에게 바치고 가는 것을 보고, “새도 임금에게 바치는데 나는 불우(不遇)하다.”고 탄식하였다.
  - key: '[주-D017] 궁궐에 …… 하였더니 : '
    value: 한나라 왕 선술(仙術)이 있었는데 업현(鄴縣)에 수령으로 있으면서 한 달에 한 번씩 서울에 와서 조회하였다. 임금이 괴이 여겨서 정탐을 시켜본즉 푸른 오리[鳧]를 타고 왕래하는 것이었다. 오리를 잡아 보니 그것은 신[履]이었다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 왕자(王者)는 …… 것이니 : '
    value: 주 성왕(周成王)이 어릴 때에 아우 강숙(康叔)과 희롱하면서 오동잎을 깎아 규(圭)를 만들어, “이것으로 너를 봉하여 주리라.” 하였더니 주공(周公)이 강숙을 봉하기를 청한즉 성왕은, “희롱으로 한 말이오.” 하였다. 주공은, “왕(王)은 희롱하는 말이 없습니다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 방외(方外)의 …… 숨기를 : '
    value: 한나라 동방삭(東方朔)이 금마문에 크게 숨었다[大隱金馬門] 한다. 그것은 궁중에 시종(侍從)으로 있어도 곧 숨어 사는 것이나 다름이 없다는 뜻이다.
english:
  title: Memorial on Behalf of Another to a Certain Official
  author: Lim Chun
  language: eng
  text: |-
    A split gourd lacks all purpose, yet finds its place in rivers and lakes; molten gold brings no blessing, and I humbly beg leave to leap forth from the furnace of fate. I dare to lay bare my utmost sincerity, and presume upon your boundless compassion.

    Consider: in an age of sage wisdom, fortune is hard-won yet easily lost. Among talented scholars, few achieve renown while many languish in obscurity. Jia Yi possessed great gifts, yet his destiny grew thin under the House of Emperor Wen. Ma Zhou attained high position, yet his life was cut short in Emperor Taizong's reign. Such difficulty in meeting opportunity makes haste in seeking office imperative. When fortune's door opens, the wise cannot afford to miss the moment—yet to await the Yellow River's clarity has moved ancient worthies to lament. Still, among scholars there is no vast gulf between the capable and incapable; in fate's ledger, fortune and misfortune diverge by turns. One word from a sage can elevate a man to the chancellor's seat, while Feng Tang endured three dynasties unwelcomed, vainly sighing as a mere court attendant.

    Yet consider Zhang Liang, humble in his cloth robes, satisfied to be enfeoffed as a marquis of ten thousand households. Kim Il-je emerged from captive lands to have seven generations serve within the palace. Li Guang, with his monkey arms and matchless archery, was nonetheless shackled by cruel fortune. Though Han Yu leaped like a tiger through towering prose, he too faced demotion and age. Without someone to lift us up, to lend us aid, how can we escape the necessity of displaying ourselves and hawking our own worth?

    Thus Maosui begged to go with the Lord of Pingyuan, likening himself to an awl's point in a sack. Feng Xuan sought audience with Mengchangjun, his heart breaking with the song of a cutting sword. To accomplish anything, one must have a knowing friend. As for myself, though my understanding is meager and my talents lack even one inch of merit, loyalty and filial piety are gathered in my house. I have long desired to serve my sovereign with unflinching devotion, and through the study of letters, to illuminate the realm and enter office.

    Recently, when the decree for examination was proclaimed, I chanced to prevail in that literary contest. Though I cannot ascend from level ground to azure clouds, I rejoice that my name appears in yellow upon the register before all other scholars. Now I understand the nobility of scholarship and am strengthened in my resolve to repay my sovereign's grace. As an attendant in the crimson halls, promoted among the stellar officials, I know that houses of accumulated virtue must receive lingering blessings. Already I have glimpsed Yu Gong's hidden merit—how should I not aspire to drag my long robes at the gates of kings? Having grasped Zou Yang's great ambitions, my peers regard me with hope, and all kinfolk rejoice. This came upon me suddenly, not through introduction by those near the throne.

    When duty called me to serve in distant provinces, I was permitted to govern in the southern realm—the very place my father once administered, where echoes of his benevolence still linger. The people's welfare remains unchanged, and though their years are hard-pressed, I may at least ensure they do not forget. Though men depart, their memory endures—perhaps I shall not shame the precedent of Xie An.

    When matters touch upon profit and loss, one often offends the powerful. Rather than yield to such pressure, I seek to repay the state with faithful service. I might request to govern a troubled commandery—is this not the mind of Zhang Chang? Yet my heart yearns for court, harboring early the desire of Xiao Lang. To spend one's days in minor counties is merely labor; can a mere clerk's post truly bring joy? I gaze toward the palace towers with suspended heart, awaiting summons to the Hall of Proclaimed Righteousness. How much more so, when memory of ancient service in the inner chambers—managing even the temple halls—meant standing ever near the imperial countenance, never distant by a finger's breadth, only to follow the sovereign into remote regions and be cut off from the radiance of the imperial presence? The vast ocean margin stretches thousands of li—my longing for the dragon face is like three autumns compressed into one day. Grief increases for this loyal steed, yet I have no wind and cloud to bring me home. At court I lack patrons of gold and silver; in myself I have no friends to arrange my fortune. My mournful cry rings out with none to answer, no way to receive gentle aid.

    I envy the white crane of Tong Pass, able to enter and offer gifts at the capital. I admire the flying duck of Ye County, which visits the palace chambers each dawn. Recently, coming from the great garrison, I journeyed to Chang'an for audience. The ethereal realm of heaven seemed a dream made tangible, and the sovereign's earnest words fell warm as spring upon my heart. He spoke as though my term would not even wait for the common cycle of replacement—how this words lifted me! For the Son of Heaven's words are never mere sport. I rejoice to find the path to advancement lies open, yet fear that external fortune cannot be commanded, and worry that my journey may not be directed by human hand.

    Observing recent practice, many talented men have been elevated to waiting posts. Whenever office falls vacant, candidates contend. Should not one seek worthy recluses to fill vain positions, replacing the incapable who waste their posts? This alone would be cause for joy! The loyal minister does not choose his task but accepts his duty. Though commands come from east or west, I shall obey. The superior man employs each according to his gifts—thus do great and small talents find their proper station. Yet my rank is humble and my person insignificant; the palace stands deep and heaven seems far. Long have I harbored this plea but lacked means to voice my true feelings.

    I humbly regard the distinguished official: possessed of innate wisdom and manifold talents, versed in the heart-essence taught by the Yellow-Headed Master, inheriting the brush-method of the White Cloud Sage. Facing north to receive instruction as a disciple, even Tang Yao sought counsel from Niexue. Resting with head to the south, even the Yellow Emperor once journeyed to Kongtong to ask of the Way. You have been granted to dwell in the realm beyond the dusty world, yet permitted to remain hidden within the palace—so is the Way supremely empty, responding to all things; so is your position exalted, yet you humble yourself before all people. You are the gathering place of all scholars, the blessing of all creatures.

    Though I am unworthy, bearing foolish qualities that merit no regard, I have long received your extraordinary attention. When I first passed the examination, you in your generosity sent aid from the imperial treasury to assist in my celebration. Your kindness knows no measure, and my gratitude is boundless. My widowed mother wept with joy, and all who heard of it shared in the honor.

    Then, in the year of Danel, when I received appointment to the Eastern Capital, the circumstances seemed right for transfer, yet obstacles arose. Only through your benevolent intervention was I removed to a more favorable position. Looking back upon this chain of fortunate encounters, I see they transcend ordinary favor. Therefore, trusting in your deep regard, I now lay bare my deepest concerns.

    I humbly beseech you: extend your rescue without abandonment; grant your mercy and pardon. I ask that you, as a matter of public trust, present my case to the throne, that I might be recalled to the palace. Should you permit me to witness the treasured sword's thrust toward heaven reaching the stars themselves, and prevent this humble creature's wings from beating empty dreams of the Milky Way—should you further elevate me and grant me to complete my service faithfully, then with all the strength I can muster, I shall serve without bringing shame upon your judgment of men. I swear by my body reduced to powder that I shall make this my sacred pledge of loyal service.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The gourd and furnace: A reference to Zhuangzi''s parable where Huizi finds his enormous gourd useless, and Zhuangzi suggests using it as a flotation device on rivers and lakes—representing finding one''s proper place despite seeming worthlessness.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Jia Yi and Ma Zhou: Historical figures who despite their talents faced short lives and difficult circumstances, illustrating the unpredictability of fortune in official service.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Zhang Liang: A famous minister who rose from humble cloth-wearer status to high office, satisfied with his elevation.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Yu Gong''s hidden merit: A reference to Yu Gong, a virtuous official whose acts of mercy led to his descendants'' flourishing—representing how virtue begets fortune across generations.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The palace towers and Hall of Proclaimed Righteousness: The writer expresses longing to serve at the imperial court rather than in provincial posts.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The white crane and flying duck: Legendary creatures able to access the imperial presence, used metaphorically to express the writer''s frustration at being distant from court.'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The yellow-headed master and white cloud sage: Figures representing Daoist wisdom, suggesting the official''s spiritual cultivation and knowledge.'
